## Phase 0 – First 1–3 Months – Mindset + Setup + Strong Start (Must Do First)

### 1. Simple & Powerful Mindset (Read This Every Day)
- You are not late — first year is the perfect time to start AI/ML  
- No zero days — even 30 minutes daily is progress  
- Compare only with yourself last week — not with anyone else  
- College exams & internals are important — keep CGPA 7.0+  
- Mistakes are okay — every error teaches you something  
- Small daily work = compound magic (like saving money — small amounts grow big)  
- Balance is secret: code + college + health + friends + family + rest  
- Your future = 70% self-learning + 20% projects + 10% college degree  

### 2. Easy Tracking – Keep It Simple (No Overload)
Use one Google Sheet, Notion page, or even notebook.  
Every week write these 6 things (takes 5 minutes):  
- Week number  
- How many DSA problems I solved this week  
- What project or coding I did  
- Hours I studied/coded  
- One good thing I did  
- One thing I can improve  

Every Sunday spend 15 minutes:  
- See last week  
- Re-do 3–5 problems you found hard  
- Plan next 7 days (example: “finish calculator project + 10 easy problems”)  

This tracking gives you motivation and shows progress.

### 3. Setup Everything (Do in First 7–10 Days)
- Laptop: Download Python 3.11+ (python.org)  
- Editor: VS Code (free, best for beginners)  
- GitHub account (username simple: yourname-aiml)  
- LinkedIn account (headline: "B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | Learning Python & AI/ML")  
- LeetCode / CodeChef / HackerRank account  
- Kaggle account (very important for ML)  
- Google Drive / OneDrive for notes & backups  

### 4. Daily Time Table Options (Choose One – Stick 80% Days)
Option 1 – Very Busy College Days (45 min–1 hour)  
- 20–30 min Python / DSA practice  
- 15–20 min watch short video  
- 10 min revise previous day  

Option 2 – Normal Days (1.5–2.5 hours)  
- 40–60 min Python or DSA coding  
- 30–45 min watch video / read notes  
- 20–30 min small project or revision  

Option 3 – Free Days / Weekends (3–5 hours)  
- 1–1.5 hours DSA / Python practice  
- 1 hour project building  
- 45 min ML intro video  
- 30 min GitHub push or notes  

### 5. Health & Balance – Never Ignore This
- Sleep 7–8 hours every night — very important for brain  
- Walk / play / exercise 20–40 minutes daily  
- Drink 2–3 liters water  
- One light day per week (only revision + relax)  
- Eat normal home food — avoid too much junk  
- Talk to friends/family — don’t sit alone coding 24/7  
- If tired or stressed — take break, watch movie, sleep extra  

Phase 1 – Months 1–6 (First Year – Build Strong Base)

1. Learn Python Very Well (Most Important for AIML)  
Python is the main language for AI/ML — master it first.

Step-by-Step Learning Order  
1. Install Python + VS Code (1 day)  
2. Hello World, print, input, comments  
3. Variables, data types (int, float, str, bool, None)  
4. Operators (arithmetic, comparison, logical)  
5. If-else, elif, nested if  
6. Loops: for range, while, break, continue, pass  
7. Lists: create, append, pop, slice, loop, list methods  
8. Tuples: immutable lists  
9. Dictionaries: key-value, get, items, update  
10. Sets: unique elements, union, intersection  
11. Functions: def, return, default args, *args, **kwargs  
12. Strings: upper/lower, split, join, replace, find, format  
13. File handling: open/read/write/close txt files  
14. Basic OOP: class, object, __init__, self, methods  
15. Modules: import math, random, datetime, os  
16. Exception handling: try, except, finally, raise  
17. List/dict comprehension  
18. Lambda functions  

Resources (Free & Super Easy)  
- CodeWithHarry Python full course (Hindi – best for Indian students)  
- Apna College Python playlist (Hindi/English)  
- freeCodeCamp Python for Beginners (English)  
- Automate the Boring Stuff with Python (free online book)  
- W3Schools Python (quick reference)  

Goal after 3–4 months:  
- Write small programs without seeing video  
- Solve basic problems like calculator, guessing game, pattern print, student manager  

2. Start Easy DSA in Python  
DSA is important even for AI/ML jobs (interviews ask logic)

Platforms (Free)  
- CodeChef Starters contests  
- LeetCode easy section  
- GeeksforGeeks beginner practice  
- HackerRank Python domain  

First 6 Months Topics (Only Easy Level)  
- Pattern printing (stars, numbers, alphabet)  
- Basic math problems (prime check, factorial, sum of digits, reverse number)  
- Arrays/lists (sum, max/min, second max, reverse, rotate left/right)  
- Strings (palindrome, count vowels, reverse words, anagram check)  
- Simple recursion (factorial, fibonacci, sum of digits)  
- Basic searching (linear search)  
- Basic sorting (bubble sort intro)  

Target: 150–300 easy problems  
Do 4–7 problems per week  
Rule: Think 15–20 min first → if stuck see hint → try again → see solution  

3. First Small Projects (Python Only)  
Do 5–8 small projects in first year — these build confidence.

Project Ideas (Easy to Medium)  
1. Number Guessing Game (computer thinks number, you guess)  
2. To-Do List Manager (add, delete, show, save to file)  
3. Quiz Game (10 MCQ questions, score system)  
4. Student Marks System (add student, show marks, average, topper)  
5. Simple Calculator (add, subtract, multiply, divide, power)  
6. Password Generator (random strong passwords)  
7. Rock Paper Scissors Game (play with computer)  
8. Currency Converter (hardcode 5–6 currencies)  

Rule  
- Finish one project every 4–6 weeks  
- Put every project on GitHub  
- Make simple README: what it does, how to run, screenshot  

4. Start AI/ML Basics (No Math Pressure Yet)  
Just understand concepts — no heavy coding yet.

What to Learn (Very Simple)  
- What is AI? (machines doing smart things like humans)  
- What is Machine Learning? (computer learns from data/examples)  
- Types of ML: supervised (labeled data), unsupervised (no labels), reinforcement  
- What is data? (numbers, text, images, videos)  
- Simple libraries intro: numpy (fast arrays), pandas (data tables)  

Resources  
- Apna College AI/ML intro playlist (Hindi – super easy)  
- CodeWithHarry Machine Learning intro (Hindi)  
- 3Blue1Brown Neural Network series (English, beautiful videos)  
- Kaggle Intro to Machine Learning course (free, very simple)  

Goal  
- Understand: ML = computer learns patterns from data  
- Know difference: AI > ML > Deep Learning  

Phase 2 – Months 7–12 (End First Year to Mid Second Year – Go Deeper)

1. DSA – Move to Medium Slowly  
Now increase difficulty — but slowly, no rush.

Topics  
Months 7–9  
- Advanced arrays: Kadane algorithm, sliding window, two pointers  
- Binary search medium problems  
- Linked list basics (reverse, cycle detection)  
- Stack & Queue simple (next greater, valid parentheses)  

Months 10–12  
- Recursion medium (subsets, permutations easy)  
- Trees basics (traversal pre/in/post, height)  
- Graphs intro (BFS/DFS on grid)  

Target: 400–600 total problems (250–400 medium)  

Resources  
- Striver SDE Sheet (only easy-medium part)  
- Love Babbar 450 (select easy-medium)  
- takeUforward YouTube  

Rule: Solve 5–8 problems per week. Focus on understanding pattern.

2. Full Python for AI/ML  
Now go deeper — these libraries are must for ML.

- Numpy full: arrays, indexing, broadcasting, math functions  
- Pandas full: read CSV/Excel, clean missing values, groupby, merge, pivot  
- Matplotlib/Seaborn: line/bar plots, scatter, histograms, pairplot  
- Scikit-learn basics: preprocessing, train_test_split, metrics  

Resources  
- Kaggle Python course (free, hands-on)  
- Kaggle Pandas course  
- CampusX YouTube ML playlist (Hindi)  
- freeCodeCamp Data Analysis with Python  

Practice  
- Download any Kaggle dataset  
- Clean data with pandas  
- Make 8–10 different plots  
- Do simple analysis (average, group by category)  

3. First Real ML Projects (Hands-On)  
Do 5–8 simple but good projects — these make your resume strong.

Projects Ideas  
1. House price prediction (linear regression)  
2. Titanic survival prediction (classification)  
3. Iris flower species classification  
4. Breast cancer diagnosis prediction  
5. Diabetes risk prediction  
6. Customer churn prediction (bank/telecom)  
7. Wine quality prediction (regression)  
8. Heart disease risk prediction  

Where to Get Data  
- Kaggle.com (search dataset name + download CSV)  

Goal for Each Project  
- Load data with pandas  
- Explore & clean  
- Train 2–3 models (logistic, decision tree, random forest)  
- Compare accuracy/F1 score  
- Make notebook clean  
- Deploy simple app with Streamlit (very easy)  

Phase 3 – Second Year – Become Strong Intermediate in AIML

1. DSA – Medium Comfortable  
- Trees medium: level order, zigzag, diameter  
- Graphs medium: shortest path, cycle detection  
- Greedy medium  
- DP 1D intro (climbing stairs, house robber)  

Target: 700–1000 total (500+ medium, 100–200 hard)

2. Machine Learning Intermediate  
- Feature engineering (scaling, encoding, feature selection)  
- Ensemble methods (Random Forest tuning, XGBoost basics)  
